habitat_description:
The range of the cat-eyed snake extends from southern Texas into Mexico; north to Sinaloa on the Pacific slope, and to Central America; Colombia, Venezuela, Ecuador, and northern Peru in northwestern South America. Campbell (1998) reported the range to extend from Nayarit and Veracruz, Mexico, to Costa Rica.

This species is primarily considered arboreal in most of its range, but it is also associated with fallen logs, debris, standing snag, and hollow trees. Its habitat consists of riparian zones, shrubland, chaparral, and hardwood woodland. In more detail, the habitat includes tropical wet, moist, and dry forest. Also, in subtropical wet and moist forest at moderate to low elevations. In Texas, populations are found among thorn brush thickets bordering ponds and streams. In Mexico, its habitat includes cloud forest openings (Campbell 1998; Ernst and Ernst 2003; Werler and Dixon 2000). This species occurs in association to areas in the vicinity of breeding aggregations of frogs (Campbell 1998; Lee 2000 (EMLB Reptile Database).
